   "source": [
    "# Notebook 1 - Fake News Data Sets Preprocessing and Exploration\n",
    "## **“Truth or Deception: A Scalable Approach to Fake News Detection with Ethical AI”**\n",
    "\n",
    "### By: FNF - Fake News Fighter\n",
    "Team Members: Sofiia Karnaukhova, Tim Gotschim, Felix Gehmair, Marcel Tobler"
    "Notebook done by Sofiia Karnaukhova"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### **Problem/Opportunity Statement:** \n",
    "\n",
    "The rapid spreading of fake news poses a significant threat to society by spreading misinformation, influencing public opinion, and undermining trust in legitimate news sources. During critical events such as elections or public health crises like COVID-19, false information can circulate faster than factual reporting, leading to confusion and potentially harmful decisions. This \"information disorder\" not only challenges democratic processes and public safety but also creates business risks, as online advertising systems often reward sensational or misleading content with increased revenue.\n",
    "\n",
    "Despite growing awareness, distinguishing between real and fake news remains difficult for both individuals and organizations due to the sophisticated nature of misinformation and the sheer volume of content published daily. Existing manual fact-checking efforts are insufficient at scale, highlighting the need for automated, scalable solutions.\n",
    "\n",
    "Our project addresses this opportunity by leveraging big data and machine learning techniques—specifically, scalable Apache Spark pipelines and advanced classification algorithms to accurately detect and classify fake news articles. By combining text analysis with wordclouds, sentiment detection, and model evaluation on large, diverse datasets (such as ISOT and WELFake), we aim to contribute a tool for early identification of misinformation. This initiative not only supports societal goals of truthfulness and informed decision making but also offers practical value for media organizations, technology platforms, and researchers seeking to combat the spread of fake news"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### **Our approach and methodology:** \n",
    "\n",
    "Our approach to fake news classification begins with collecting and preparing two large and diverse datasets: the ISOT Fake News Dataset and the WELFake Dataset (for evaluation purposes). We first combine and shuffle the data, as well as convert the labels into a binary format to support classification tasks. Then we ensure data quality by removing entries with missing titles or text, then normalize the text by converting it to lowercase and removing punctuation, numbers, and stopwords to reduce noise, as well as delete mentions of specific sources like \"Reuters -\" in true news to avoid bias in further classification. We further process the text through lemmatization and later on with pipeline tokenization, which standardizes word forms and helps the model focus on meaningful patterns. \n",
    "\n",
    "For feature engineering, we transform the cleaned text into numerical representations using TF-IDF, which captures the importance of words within each article. With these features, we train several machine learning models, including Logistic regression, Naive Bayes, Decision Tree and Random Forest. We use Apache Spark to efficiently handle the large datasets and to scale our experiments.\n",
    "\n",
    "To evaluate our models, we split the data into training and test sets. We prioritize recall as our main evaluation metric, aiming to minimize the number of fake news articles that go undetected, but we also analyze other metrics such as precision, accuracy, and the confusion matrix for a comprehensive assessment. To further test our models' generalizability, we evaluate them on the WELFake dataset, which was not used during training.To enrich our model and explore the role of emotional tone, we also extract sentiment features from the articles.\n",
    "\n",
    "Throughout the project, we pay careful attention to ethical and legal considerations, ensuring compliance with dataset licenses and reflecting on potential biases in our data and models. We document our process, results, and any limitations to promote transparency and responsible use of our fake news detection system."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### **Context of the Notebook 1:**\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook is the first part of our fake news classification project. Here, we focus on loading the datasets, exploring what the data looks like, and cleaning the news articles to get them ready for analysis. We remove things like missing values, punctuation, and stopwords, and we also look at how the data is distributed between real and fake news. The goal of this notebook is to make sure our data is clean and well-organized before we move on to building and testing machine learning models in the next steps."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## **Environment Setup**"
