    "#### Registration of our User-Defined Functions located in the preprocessing_fake_news with Spark Context"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we are importing necessary components for creating and using PySpark UDFs, like **udf** to define user-defined functions for DataFrame transformations, **StringType** to specify the return type of our UDFs as in our case we are only returning strings and the custom preprocessing module written by us, named **preprocessing_fake_news** as **pp** which contains text processing functions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Importing the udf, StringType, and pp modules\n",
    "from pyspark.sql.functions import udf\n",
    "from pyspark.sql.types import StringType\n",
    "import preprocessing_fake_news as pp"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "First, we define a function to detect the language called **check_lang**, specifically we are detecting english language, of a given text string using a language identifier."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "check_lang_udf = udf(pp.check_lang, StringType())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next, we define the function called **remove_stops**, which removes English stopwords from the input string. To handle invalid or problematic input, it returns an empty string if the input is not a valid string. The function then splits the text into words, filters out the stopwords, and recombines the remaining words into a cleaned output string.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "remove_stops_udf = udf(pp.remove_stops, StringType())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next we define **remove_features** function that cleans the input text by converting it to lowercase and removing URLs, @mentions, punctuation, and numeric tokens using regular expressions. It then filters out words that are shorter than three characters or contain non-alphanumeric characters. Finally, it returns the cleaned text as a single string.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "remove_features_udf = udf(pp.remove_features, StringType())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As the next udf we define **tag_and_remove** function that tags the input text and keeps only nouns, verbs, and adjectives. It returns an empty string for invalid input to cope with possible exceptions. After tagging, it filters words by their POS tags and returns the filtered words as a string."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "tag_and_remove_udf = udf(pp.tag_and_remove, StringType())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, defined **lemmatize** function lemmatizes words in the input text to their root forms using part-of-speech tags. It first checks for valid input and returns an empty string if invalid. The text is split into words, tagged for POS, and each word is lemmatized as a verb if its tag indicates a verb; otherwise, as a noun. The lemmatized words are then joined back into a single string and returned.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "lemmatize_udf = udf(pp.lemmatize, StringType())"
   ]
  },
  {
