  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Word Clouds"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, we want to examine the word clouds for WELFake news data. This will allow us to gain some preliminary insights into the nature and differences between fake and true news present in this dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 46,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1152x576 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Separating texts for true and fake news, filtering out None values\n",
    "true_texts = [row['text'] for row in evaluation_df.filter(evaluation_df.label == 0).select('text').collect() if row['text'] is not None]\n",
    "fake_texts = [row['text'] for row in evaluation_df.filter(evaluation_df.label == 1).select('text').collect() if row['text'] is not None]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Joining texts into one string for fake and true news\n",
    "true_text = \" \".join(true_texts)\n",
    "fake_text = \" \".join(fake_texts)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generating word clouds\n",
    "wc_true = WordCloud(width=500, height=400, background_color='white').generate(true_text)\n",
    "wc_fake = WordCloud(width=500, height=400, background_color='white').generate(fake_text)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plotting side by side for easier analysis\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 8))\n",
    "axes[0].imshow(wc_true, interpolation='bilinear')\n",
    "axes[0].set_title('True News')\n",
    "axes[0].axis('off')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].imshow(wc_fake, interpolation='bilinear')\n",
    "axes[1].set_title('Fake News')\n",
    "axes[1].axis('off')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "From the word clouds above, we can visually compare the most common words found in true news and fake news articles. Both types feature prominent terms like \"said\" , \"one\" , \"Trump\" and \"US\" indicating a shared focus on political figures and national topics. However, true news tends to emphasize institutional and formal terms such as \"White House\" , \"New York\" , \"President\" and specific days like \"Monday\" and \"Wednesday\" reflecting a focus on official reporting and event coverage. In contrast, fake news word cloud highlight more people-centric and emotive language, with words like \"people\" , \"government\" , \"group\" , \"right\" and \"women\" as well as more frequent use of terms like \"fact\" and \"story\" suggesting an emphasis on opinion, speculation, and sensationalism. This comparison reveals that while both news types discuss similar subjects, true news generally maintains a more formal and fact-driven tone, whereas fake news often adopts a more conversational and provocative style, which fully aligns with our preliminary findings based on our main ISOT dataset via word clouds."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Why WELFake dataset would be used for evaluation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We would be using the WELFake dataset for evaluation purposes to ensure that our machine learning models can generalize beyond the data they were trained on. Since WELFake contains over 70,000 news articles from multiple diverse sources, it provides a rich and varied test set that better reflects real-world news content. Evaluating our models on this external dataset would help us avoid overfitting and assess how well the models perform on previously unseen data. Additionally, WELFake is frequently updated and captures the dynamic nature of online news, which makes it ideal for testing fake news detection in a realistic, constantly evolving information environment. Using this dataset would strengthen the reliability and credibility of our results."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
